---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const acts = [
  { n: 'Act One', href: '/guide/act-1/', hook: 'The temptation: prophecy meets ambition, and a loyal soldier talks himself into murdering his king.' },
  { n: 'Act Two', href: '/guide/act-2/', hook: 'The deed: the killing happens off-stage, and the play tips from planning into guilt, knocking and disorder.' },
  { n: 'Act Three', href: '/guide/act-3/', hook: 'The tyranny: Macbeth kills to keep the crown, and discovers the killing will not stay done.' },
  { n: 'Act Four', href: '/guide/act-4/', hook: 'The unravelling: false comfort from the witches, and a slaughter that turns Scotland against its king.' },
  { n: 'Act Five', href: '/guide/act-5/', hook: 'The reckoning: guilt, isolation and nemesis close the circle the first prophecy opened.' },
];
---

<BaseLayout title="The Guide, Act by Act" active="guide" description="An act-by-act guide to Macbeth: what happens, the methods that matter, and verified quotations, built to feed the Literary Heritage coursework essay.">
  <div class="part-head">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kicker">The study guide</p>
      <h1>The guide, act by act</h1>
      <p class="lede prose">
        Five acts, one falling arc. These guides do not retell the plot for its own sake: they
        show you what each act <em>does</em> to the tragedy, and hand you the quotations and the
        analytical habits you will need when you sit down to write.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="band">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0;">How to use this guide</h2>
      <p>
        Read the act first, in your edition, before you read the guide. Then use each page in
        three passes. Start with <strong>What happens</strong> to fix the sequence of events in
        your head. Move to <strong>A closer look</strong>, where three short essays model the
        kind of argument your coursework wants: not what the scene says, but how Shakespeare
        makes it mean. Finish with the <strong>quotation table</strong>, and copy the lines that
        give you something to say into your own bank. The <strong>Think it through</strong>
        questions are there to keep the reading open; the <strong>Towards the coursework</strong>
        box turns each act back towards the essay you are building.
      </p>

      <div class="grid cols-3">
        {acts.map((a) => (
          <a class="card" href={a.href}>
            <h3>{a.n}</h3>
            <p>{a.hook}</p>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>

      <div class="box think">
        <h3>How to read a scene</h3>
        <p>
          The best method is one sentence long: <strong>move from device to effect, every
          time</strong>. Naming a device is labelling, not analysis. Spotting a metaphor,
          writing &lsquo;this is a metaphor&rsquo;, and moving on earns almost nothing, because
          it stops exactly where the thinking should start.
        </p>
        <p>
          So train the habit. When a line strikes you, ask three questions in order. What is the
          <em>method</em> (the word choice, the image, the verse or prose, the staging, the
          silence, the thing done off-stage)? What is the <em>effect</em> on an audience in the
          moment (fear, sympathy, unease, a flash of dramatic irony)? And what does that effect
          let you <em>argue</em> about the play as a whole (about kingship, about guilt, about
          what the tragedy believes)? A good paragraph is that chain, tightened: one method, one
          effect, one claim, looped back to the question you were set.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p>
        Everything here points one way. The guide is not the destination; the essay is. Each act
        page ends by folding back into the three set questions on kingship, the presentation of
        women and masculinity, so that by the time you reach the
        <a href="/coursework/">coursework page</a> you are not staring at a blank document but
        assembling an argument you have already half-made.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
